column1: What are the differences between ECU-850 and ECU-850b?,"The ECU-850b is an enhanced variant of the ECU-850 with three key upgrades: Dedicated AI Accelerator (NPU capable of 5 TOPS), Increased Memory (4 GB LPDDR4 RAM vs 2 GB), Higher Clock Speed (Cortex-A53 cores at 1.5 GHz vs 1.2 GHz).","The ECU-850b is an AI-enhanced variant of the ECU-850, featuring a dedicated NPU and upgraded hardware. The base ECU-850 provides AI/ML acceleration but lacks a dedicated NPU, while the ECU-850b includes a 5 TOPS NPU, 4 GB of RAM, and a 1.5 GHz CPU for demanding edge AI workloads.
[Source: ECU-800_Series_Base.md

column1: Compare the CAN bus capabilities of ECU-750 and ECU-850.,"The ECU-750 (700 series) has a single channel CAN FD interface with speeds up to 1 Mbps, while the ECU-850 (800 series) features a dual channel CAN FD interface with speeds up to 2 Mbps per channel. The ECU-850 offers significantly better CAN bus performance and redundancy.","The ECU-850 offers dual-channel, higher-speed CAN FD compared to the ECU-750's single-channel interface.

The ECU-750 provides a single CAN FD channel at 1 Mbps, while the ECU-850 features two independent channels each supporting up to 2 Mbps. This gives the ECU-850 greater bandwidth and capacity for complex network architectures.
[Source: ECU-700_Series_Manual.md

column1: Which ECU can operate in the harshest temperature conditions?,"The ECU-850 and ECU-850b (800 series) can operate in the harshest temperature conditions, with an operating range of -40°C to +105°C.
